Simple ways to help your child deal with tantrums
I often encounter the fact that a child's anger, a child's annoyance, is seen by parents as something wrong and abnormal.
When a child expresses anger openly, we do not know how to react, says psychologist Ekaterina Kes.
Specialist urges a little conversation about these very natural and human feelings of anger and resentment that everyone experiences periodically.
Aggression is a physical action directed against another person, and it usually occurs when we are angry.
When we adults are angry, when we're upset, we usually know what's happening to us and how to deal with it.
We can express, suppress, hide, or keep our anger and resentment in ourselves, we can tell our friends or other relatives about it, we can blow up the couch in anger, we can smoke cigarettes (not the best way to get rid of anger!), we can take a shower, we can shoot a gun at a fire, and we can do other things that we don't normally do.
We're not aggressive towards others because we know different ways of dealing with these emotions.
Children, when they're angry, don't know what's wrong with them, what to call them, how to live with them.
They may say, "Get out!" "You're a fool!" "You're a bad mother!" "I don't hurt you!" "I'm not going to hurt you!" - and very rarely, when they can say, "I'm mad at you!"
Children are literally alive, they are fully present, they are spontaneous and genuine in their feelings, and they are often in the grip of emotions.
It is vital that parents not forbid their children to express their feelings, including anger, but instead show respect and help.
