German researchers are debating the number of victims of the "Berlin Wall".
A new study suggests that the number of people killed in the former Eastern Bloc under communist rule may be much higher than previously thought, but doubts about the true number of victims remain.
According to figures released on Wednesday by the Berlin Wall Museum Checkpoint Charlie, between 1945 and 1989, 1,841 people were killed by communist authorities on the border between the western allied zones and the newly formed West Germany for trying to escape from their controlled territory.
The museum has been tracking border-related deaths for years, and it's been updating the casualty figures every few minutes.
This year, 11 more deaths were added to the list, including the death of a six-year-old boy who drowned while trying to reach his family in the West Germany through what was then Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
Among the new victims of the Berlin Wall are Soviet army deserters.
"The ultimate extent of the damage caused by the double evils of communism and socialism has not yet been fully documented", admits the museum's director, Alexandra Hildebrante.
"Our task is to ensure that the graves of those who died trying to escape the Communist-controlled state are cleaned and preserved", emphasized Hildebrandt in a statement.
But other researchers have already questioned the new figures.
"The number 1841 is inconclusive", claimed Johannes Stathus, an expert in the history of Eastern Europe at the Free University of Berlin, in an interview with the Süddeutsche Zeitung.
He and other researchers from the Free University of Berlin are currently reviewing possible suspicious deaths at the border, and have so far managed to confirm only 260 cases.
Previously, researchers estimated that 138 people were executed by the Communists at the Berlin Wall alone.
The number of people who have died trying to escape across the Baltic Sea or to reach the West through neighboring countries, the State estimates, could be as high as a thousand.
But it's still significantly lower than 1841.
One reason for the different number of victims could be the different methodologies.
The Checkpoint Charlie Museum also counts all suicides of Eastern Union border guards, whether or not they were directly related to their service.
The museum also records deaths that are not directly related to violence.
"If seniors in their 70s or 80s die of heart attacks after crossing the border", Hildebrante believes, this must be the effect of this "border of slaughter".
But the state is convinced that a distinction must be made between elderly people who may have died as a result of their experience and those who died as a result of waiting for a long time in the heat of the bus at the border.
Regardless of its victims, keeping track is not easy, since the Communist authorities in the Soviet Union did not keep such statistics, and researchers have to search for documents in various scattered archives, says Štát.
However, the State Department has recently been updating its files, and so it may soon come up with new estimates of the number of victims.
