French court rejects request to close shops in Jungle Camp.
A French court rejected a request by the Calais authorities to demolish dozens of makeshift shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp, which is home to thousands of refugees.
At a court hearing this week, the Calais government said the state should demolish 72 makeshift stores where people sell various goods such as cigarettes and energy drinks, offer freezing services, tea for 50 cents (40p) and simple meals for a few euros in makeshift restaurants.
The Prefecture of Calais indicated that these self-constructed companies had to be dismantled because they created a building economy and did not pay taxes, as well as creating fire and sanitary risks.
The representatives of the Humana group explained to the court that these small businesses are essential because the food provided by the government and the support group does not meet the needs of the camp, which continues to grow in population.
They also pointed out that self-run shops and restaurants often offer free shelter and meals to those who need it most.
The Lille court found that there was no legal basis to deport the people who had set up 72 self-help shops, but that is what the Prefect of Calais was concerned about.
Judge Jean-François Molla said that food, coffee and restaurants play a role beyond simply providing food for people who live in "extremely poor conditions".
He pointed out that these places are peaceful gathering places for refugees and volunteers.
One of the sites at risk of being overwhelmed is the Jungle Book Kids camp café, which provides over 200 free meals a day, English and French language classes and shelter counselling for hundreds of unaccompanied vulnerable minors.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect children's coffee shops.
The letter to the Guardian stated that the closure of the café "would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are as young as 8 years old".
On Friday, two charities, Aid to Refugees and L'Auberge des Migrants, reported that the number of people in the Jungle camp had risen to 9,000, the highest since the summer's surge of migrants.
