In Spain, the chances of reducing the budget deficit are jeopardised by the failure to form a government.
On 12 July the European Commission (EC) concluded that Spain and Portugal had not implemented measures of sufficient size to bring the deficit level down to the euro area's 3% of GDP target.
Despite the austerity measures implemented, Portugal's budget deficit was estimated at 4.4% of GDP at the end of last year, while Spain's was 5.1% of GDP.
However, the European Commission decided not to impose economic sanctions on both countries, while setting fiscal targets for the near term.
One of the reasons why the EC has not yet imposed sanctions on both countries is the growing Euroscepticism in many European Union countries.
Additional sanctions would only exacerbate this negative sentiment.
Critics, however, point out that the EC is inconsistent in its decisions, agreeing to a set of rules from the outset and then failing to apply them in practice.
For example, the president of Germany's Bundesbank, Jens Veidmann, has said that Europe is losing its credibility by creating the impression among its citizens that European Union rules are recommendative rather than binding.
The Commission has now proposed and all Member States have agreed to extend the deadline for closing the deficit by the end of this year for Portugal and by 2018 for Spain.
The European Commission intends to review the progress made by both countries in the coming months, while indicating that both Spain and Portugal should be prepared to introduce further savings measures if circumstances so require.
Initial projections suggest that Portugal could achieve its target on time and that the deficit could be reduced to 2,5% of GDP as early as this year.
This means that the government of this country has to implement austerity measures of 0.25% of GDP this year under the Stability Programme.
These measures should be included in this year's budget, with additional attention to controlling the cost of purchasing goods and services.
In the case of Spain, the situation is much more complex.
The budget deficit should be reduced to 4,6% of GDP this year, to 3,1% next year and to 2,2% in 2018.
In addition, for the next two years, the consolidation measures must amount to 0,5% of GDP each year.
The achievement of these objectives is made all the more difficult by the fact that it has taken eight months for the Spanish political parties to agree on the formation of a government, and the likelihood that Spain may have to hold a general election for the third time in the year is growing.
However, opinion polls show that even a third election would not significantly change the political landscape of the country.
The most popular party is still the People's Party, led by current Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy, which would again receive less than 33% of the vote.
Only the Socialists have seen a slight increase in popularity, while the anti-austerity parties Podemos (We Can) and Ciudadanos (Pilson) have seen a slight decrease.
The People's Party wants to get the Socialists and Ciudadanos into government later this month, otherwise it will not be able to adopt and submit the draft budget for 2017 to the European Commission for approval by mid-October.
As the representative of the People's Party in the parliamentary group, Rafael Hernando, has said, if the government fails to be formed and a third general election is held, Spain will become the laughingstock of Europe.
