Before the 40th anniversary of "Liv" the legendary rock group can be introduced at an exhibition in Leipzig.
The exhibition will feature various Lions' items - photographs arranged in a timeline to reflect the group's activities from its inception until 2010, when the group's closure is announced.
The exhibition will also include the stage costumes, musical instruments, decorations and concert records, as well as other items that have not yet been shown to the general public, which reflect the creative activities of the group "Livi".
The exhibition will be supplemented by objects from the collection of the Museum of Liège.
The visual design of the exhibition was made in collaboration with the fashion artist and painter Elita Patmalniec.
Musicians associated with Livy and their relatives also responded to the invitation and shared both items and memories.
The origins of "Liv" are traced back to 1972, when a vocal instrumental ensemble was formed in the Cultural House of Leiden, led by Juris Pavītols.
The ensemble in its original form took part in the festival "Liepajas dzintars" in 1972 and 1974, as well as in the city and republic shows.
In 1976, a fateful meeting took place when Juris Pavittol met Erik Kijel and founded the group at the Metallurg Cultural Palace, inviting Ingrid Gutman, Andri Kruzin and Jani Grodu to join.
Over the years, the group's composition has changed many times.
Members have joined, others have gone their way, some have returned.
However, the desire to prove that Latvian folk music is able to live and exist has remained unchanged.
"The jeans, the muffins, the beards - they're a constant, and they're not the typical orchestra boys", says music critic Klaus Wauer.
In addition to the above musicians, the band included such outstanding musicians as Igo, Vilnis Russiņš, Modris Šterns, Valdis Starks, Laimis Rācenājs, Talis Pusbarnieks, Ainars Virga, Aivars Bryzis, Guntars Mucenieks, Dainis Virga, Tomass Klein and many others.
Admission to the exhibition is free.
The exhibition is open from 19 August to 30 October.
