The state energy company Latvenergo is following the process of opening the gas market both from the consumer and potential trader's positions, said the company's press secretary Ivita Bidere.
'The decision whether Latvenergo will also join the gas market as a trader in the future will be determined by the gas market model and the legal framework that will be created.'
"We are therefore actively involved in the development and commenting of legislation and in the submission of our proposals", said Ms Bidere.
The agency BNS has already written that the Ministry of Economy (EM) in cooperation with the Public Service Regulatory Commission and the energy company "Latvijas Gāze" has developed a draft Cabinet regulation "Regulations for the sale and use of natural gas" that will change the existing principles of the natural gas market operation, from 3 April 2017, providing natural gas users with the right to freely choose a natural gas trader.
In working towards the new regulation of the natural gas market, the EM aims to make the process of natural gas trading as simple and user-friendly as possible.
The most efficient and user-friendly service solution was therefore the 'dealer-centric model' in which all customer service activities are provided by the distributor - one contract, one invoice and one information and customer service point, leaving the technical aspects of the natural gas distribution system to the distribution system operator.
A similar solution is currently being implemented in electricity trading.
It is recalled that the market opening to household customers is intended to be gradual, i.e. after 3 April 2017 household customers who do not wish to choose another natural gas trader will be able to continue to receive natural gas from an existing trader at regulated price, thus becoming connected customers.
'In this case, the obligation to supply natural gas to related users at a regulated price is imposed on the public trader', the Ministry informed.
Traders will have to choose a natural gas trader with whom to conclude a natural gas trading contract.
For a certain period of time until the conclusion of the gas trading contract, traders will be supplied with natural gas at a fixed price by the existing natural gas trader.
The draft rules of the Cabinet detail the rights and obligations of the natural gas distributor, system operator and user.
The rules shall specify the procedures for the supply of natural gas to users and its interruption, the requirements for the safe use of the natural gas system, the rights and obligations of the trader, the public marketer, the system operator, the user and the owner of the gasified facility in the supply and use of natural gas; the procedures for settling the services received, the interest rate for delay, the change of traders and the procedures for supplying users in the event of a disruption in the supply of natural gas; the procedures for ensuring the provision of a public market to users connected to the supply of natural gas.
