NASA climate model: Venus was once a habitable planet
Based on NASA's latest climate models, Venus was once a habitable planet.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to study the history of Venus using tools and algorithms that climate scientists use.
The model was developed to determine whether conditions on Venus, which has a hot, water-free surface and an atmosphere composed almost entirely of carbon, had ever been similar to those on Earth.
Scientists have previously suggested that the slow rotation of Venus is due to a thick atmosphere.
But the latest simulations suggest that Venus once had a flat, Earth-like atmosphere, and that it was slowly breaking up.
The model also looks at the early topography of Venus.
It had more land area than Earth, but it had enough water and geographical diversity to support life and prevent water from evaporating.
In the early days of Venus, the Sun was 30 percent brighter.
In a GISS model simulation of the rotation of Venus, the model reveals that the light of the day on it lasts for 2 months, explained GISS scientist Antonius Del Genio in a press release.
This process heats the planet's surface and produces rain, which in turn forms thick layers of clouds that act as a rain screen, shielding the planet from the sun's heat.
The result is a temperate climate, actually a few degrees below the temperature on Earth today.
The model portrays the history of Venus, similar to the theory of evolution that scientists have developed in their hypotheses.
Though it was once habitable, for several billion years Venus was subjected to excessive heat and ultraviolet rays.
Its oceans were scorched, and its mountains were scorched by ultraviolet light.
When the water was completely evaporated, all that remained was a thin atmosphere of carbon dioxide, a deadly greenhouse gas, the Venus we know today.
The scientists have published the results of their new model of the climate of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
