Kepler measured the rotation rate of stars in the constellation Pleiades.
The latest mission of the Kepler telescope has helped astronomers compile the most comprehensive catalog of the rotation rates of stars in the Pleiades constellation.
The new data help astronomers understand why stars in this star rotate at different speeds, and how the rotation rate of stars can be related to planet formation.
"We hope that by comparing our results with those of other stars, we will gain a broader understanding of the relationship between the mass of the stars, their ages, and even the history of the solar system", said Luis Rebula, a scientist at the Caltech Infrared Process and Analysis Center in Pasadena, California.
The comet is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in this galaxy are just beginning to grow, reaching an age of about 125 million years.
They're spinning at full speed.
At their maximum velocity, these rising stars are dispersed by a large amount of stellar wind.
When the waves enter the magnetic field of the stars, they slow the stars down.
As stars age, their rotational speed decreases.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by determining the time between the appearance of a recognizable stellar neighborhood, such as the solar plane.
The latest star rotation rate catalogue shows that larger stars rotate more slowly than smaller stars.
Rebul compares the stars to the dancers, and the taller dancers do the pirouettes slower than the shorter dancers.
Rebul says that the "ballet" of the Pleiades shows that slowly rotating objects are larger and more massive, while faster- rotating objects are very small stars.
Because of its proximity, the Pleiades star serves as a magnificent space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with their rotational speeds.
Rebul says that Pleiades' star helps to create theoretical models of the rotation of stars in both directions for both older and younger stars.
We still have much to learn about how, when, and why stars slow down and stop spinning completely.
Rebuls and his colleagues have detailed their analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiades in three new publications that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
